<p align='center'><font color='#0e024d' face='Arial'><strong>THE FAILURE OF THE CURRENT GM SYSTEM - OCTOBER 10, 1999</strong></font></p>
<hr size='1' width='85%'>
<table border='0' width='85%'>
  <tr>
<td valign='top' align='left'><font face='Arial'><small>
Firstly let me explain that the following editorial is not a simple rant.  I have tried to keep it in its objective context, however a great deal of it does relate specifically to events on the Povar server in which I was involved.  This editorial is aimed to highlight the desperate need for a restructuring of the GM system, and the need for publicized and uniform GM policy.
<P>
It was my sad and unfortunate experience to be involved very recently on an attempt to enter the much-debated zone of the Plane of Fear.  Now in recent times it has become more and more apparent that there are no plans in the very near future to cater to the growing number of high level (level 49+) players on the servers.  The current level 49+ zones of Solusek B and Lower Guk are almost always overflowing beyond their spawn capacity, Kedge Keep still after all this time remains unitemised, and the dragons spawn only once a week.  The fire giant spawn in Solusek B is still problematic with both its AI and pathing, and when the zone isn’t spiking from strange lag bubbles or you can’t see half the people in your group because of zone visibility bugs, your corpse is stuck in some wall while you twiddle your thumbs waiting for a GM to log on 10 minutes after your 2 hour resurrection limit has expired.  In short, there is a desperate need for a high level area.  Before you say “Ahh but the Plane of Hate is coming!” keep in mind it will most likely be as difficult if not more so than the existing Plane of Fear, and the issues I am going to discuss will apply to it equally.
<P>
So with nothing left to do in an already overcrowded environment, a group of 24 seasoned players decided to attempt a Plane of Fear break in.  Now keep in mind that we are not talking newbies here.  Every player has at least 40 days play time.  Every one was level 49 or 50.  Every one knew not only how to play their character but how to play them well.  All that said and done, the break in attempt was disastrous.  After sending in a monk to feign and scout the area we entered the gate en masse.  It is here that the true contentious events of this evening begin to unfold.  <b>Every single player was dumped by the Verant server upon zoning</b>.  I am not saying gradual packet loss resulting in linkdeath – I am referring to an instantaneous dump to the not responding screen.  Every single player died.  If they didn’t die immediately they died as they relogged in one by one into a hostile environment with absolutely no backup.  
<P>
Now lets just make something clear here.  We are talking players from around the world, on different links ranging from modem to t1 and cable.  On computers of varying performance, the majority though high-end (we are hardcore gamers after all) and <b>every single one was dumped alike</b>.  
<P>
We petitioned to the GM’s for assistance in corpse retrieval.  The deaths were caused by either instability with the zone or a latent defect in the code of the game that causes zone dumps when too many people attempt to zone into it at once.  These are problems caused by Verant / Red Eye.  These are the reason (so we would believe) that GM’s are in place.  To assist and facilitate players who suffer loss as a result of fault on the part of game rather than the player.  The players in this instance had no opportunity whatsoever to even defend themselves – these deaths were purely the result of a problem on Verant’s part.
<P>
Of course the guides at first gave us the usual run around.  I am going to deal very quickly with the guides here and now.  Guides are generally players who have a clue about the real game itself.  They donate their time to pull corpses from walls, deal with harassment and exploit reports, and otherwise assist the newbies of Norrath.  The guides generally do a great job and are unpaid for their labours (unlike server GM’s who are employed by Verant).  All of this work by the guides is supposedly meant to assist the lead GM of the server to have more time for dynamic quests and supporting the players in large-scale bug issues such as what occurred with this days Plane of Fear problem.  Povar has had less than 10 dynamic quests since the server went live.  So if this is a reason for the <b>paid employment</b> of server GM’s then its good to know the money is being well spent (not).  On the other hand the response of our server GM Camii to large-scale bug related issues seems to depend on whether or not she got out on the right side of the bed that morning.
<P>
GM Camii eventually logged on to the server in invisible mode.  I messaged her in relation to the issue after the guide so persistently told me that there would be no assistance.  GM Camii first asked what had happened and I explained that the deaths had occurred from zone dumping.  She then said that there would be no help with corpse recovery since there had not been a bug.  I asked how this could not be a bug, she replied that the zone itself had not crashed, the only bug in fear that was known to cause zone failure had been fixed and that was the end of the matter.  I was not going to accept this so I questioned further as to what had caused the problem then.  She replied that the problem was most likely due to too many people trying to zone in at once.  I asked her to direct me to an official Verant publication which gave warning to players that they should not attempt to zone in with more than a specific number of players simultaneously.  She ignored this request, I can only assume it is because there isn’t one.  I then asked why there would not be any assistance again.  She replied that and I quote: <I>“Whilst some server GM’s do assist in corpse recovery for these situations, there are other Servers GM’s that do not.  <b>It is my personal choice not to</b>.”</I>  In other words, “You picked the wrong server to play on because I am not going to give you the equal footing to play on that other servers get”.  I asked her for an email address of someone I could contact at Verant in relation to the poor gm service and she would only give me her own.  I asked to speak directly to the person responsible for the policy she was applying in this instance and she replied: <i>'That would be me.'</i> <P>
Keep in mind also that this same policy had been instituted a few days earlier in Solusek B.  After taking down the zone to supposedly “fix the fire giant spawn” a number of players ended up with their corpses in lava and under numerous giants who had been broken off their path and could not return to their original spawn points.  Once again absolutely no assistance was forthcoming from the Server GM’s and the one guide who attempted to assist us was reprimanded for doing so.  It appears that GM Camii at least believes that she has the personal right to choose the footing on which we the players are permitted to play the game on what she must feel is her personal server.  I do not see how this can be endorsed by Verant as a viable means of ensuring fair policy implementation across all servers.
<P>
Also note that a different set of players had previously died in the Plane of Fear some time ago and were given a complete corpse recovery by GM Camii who claims she informed then that there would be no more corpse recoveries from this zone.  The problem is none of the players who went in on this days raid were aware of this so called policy.  Nor should they have been expected to since it is not available anywhere as a public document.  No-one who entered that gate expected to get through the day without at least a couple of deaths.  But what was not expected was that everyone would die instantly due to a bug in the game and then be told by the very GM’s we indirectly employ that they had made a personal choice to not assist us any further.  Not a choice based on any public policy we are aware of as players, but rather one made up on a whim by the Server GM. <P>

Now I will also add that later in the day a guide on the server claimed that the decision was actually from Jeff Butler, the Head of the GM division.  But GM Camii informed me directly that the choice was her personal call, and I must take that direct evidence as the more relevant factor in all of this.
<P>
In all it took over 6 hours to recover the majority of the corpses.  Everyone lost close to or more than a levels worth of experience. Many lost items that are quite difficult to obtain from corpses ending up in the middle of scareling spawn areas and were unrecoverable.  In all this time the GM’s did not lift a finger to aid us.  It is my opinion that they completely failed in their duty to ensure players can play the game free from what I will call “programming and server caused frustrating events”.  We pay to play.  We do not pay to spend hours and hours in a corpse retrieval process losing even more hours of experience because of a fault in the zoning system not warned or mentioned of anywhere on any Verant information release, and then told on the whim of a server GM that they don’t feel like helping us today.
<P>
What has to occur in the very near future if Verant wishes to retain the players that have made Everquest the success it is, is that a <b>publicly released policy set</b> needs to be drawn up and made available to players.  I am not talking about leaked customer service manuals (although that was certainly insightful on how Verant views us the players).  I am talking about a document I can print out which tells me exactly what a GM can and can’t do and which applies across all servers uniformly.  It shouldn’t matter that my GM got out of bed and has a headache or is hungover.  It shouldn’t matter that I chose to play on Povar instead of say Fennin Ro or Veeshan (these are picked at random – no hidden meaning is being suggested here).  It shouldn’t matter that I have GM Camii instead of GM Helpful as my server GM.  I should be able to look in my document and see exactly what things a GM will and will not assist me including numerous example scenarios.  I should be able to download daily a list of known things that will cause a client crash so that I am aware of them.  
<P>
In short we need a number of things to change.  Firstly we need to get a clear list of uniform GM rules and responsibilities available to the public.   We should know exactly <b>why</b> GM’s are in the game.  Because if all they are there to do is pull corpses out of walls (which the guides always do anyway, not the server GM’s)  then Verant may as well sack them all and spend the money on some more coders to finish off the zones and fix the bugs.  Secondly we need a clear means of contacting the people who manage the Server GM’s, that is, their boss.  We need to have a means of reporting on how we feel GM’s are fulfilling the role defined by them in the document I have listed above.
<P>
We pay to play.  Server GM’s are paid to ensure we can play free from hindrance of problems caused by code or bug related problems.  Having to spend an entire day being told by GM’s that they <b>choose</b> not to help the players who have made the game what it is today for no other reason I can discern except that they don’t feel like it (from the statement made to me by GM Camii) is quite simply unacceptable.  If this is not the reason GM’s are in game then we the players deserve to be told exactly why they are there and what their job is <b>in writing</b>.  This whole saga has completely undermined my faith in the GM system as a whole.  Alienating the high level player base is certainly one way to deal with the lack of high level areas and activities – because sooner or later they will all quit the game.  
<P>
In conclusion I welcome an official response from Verant on this editorial and have notified them of it’s posting.  I also welcome any other reasoned and well worded response for or against my point of view and will post them up if sent to me.  My aim here is to get the problems fixed.  What happened with this event should not have.  The GM’s made a wrong decision and they are going to have to live with that for at least the rest of their time on Povar.  It is time for Verant to acknowledge they have some responsibilities to us as paying players, and release to the public the material I have discussed above.  They also need to provide a proper system of complaint so that GM’s are accountable when they fail to fulfil these responsibilities.   Hopefully this will occur before complete faith is lost in an already very unpredictable and unreliable customer service department.
<P>
